    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>Any use of any of the methods suggested is considered a code smell which is based in a bad OO design.</p>\n\n<p>If your design is good, you should not find yourself needing to use <code>getClass()</code> or <code>instanceof</code>.</p>\n\n<p>Any of the suggested methods will do, but just something to keep in mind, design-wise.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 9049,
      "reputation" : 16608,
      "user_id" : 16542,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 73,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/utKnQ.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Andreas Petersson",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/16542/andreas-petersson"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 13,
    "last_activity_date" : 1398795686,
    "last_edit_date" : 1398795686,
    "creation_date" : 1234454672,
    "answer_id" : 542004,
    "question_id" : 541749,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>There is also an <a href=\"http://java.sun.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/lang/Class.html#isInstance(java.lang.Object)\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><code>.isInstance</code></a> method on the \"<code>Class</code>\" class. if you get an object's class via <code>myBanana.getClass()</code> you can see if your object <code>myApple</code> is an instance of the same class as <code>myBanana</code> via</p>\n\n<pre><code>myBanana.getClass().isInstance(myApple)\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
